# Semantic HTML and SEO

## Semantic HTML (current standards)

- **Structure**: Use `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>` to delimit regions.
- **Headings**: One `<h1>` per page (main name/title); logical hierarchy `<h2>` â†’ `<h3>`.
- **Navigation**: Main links in `<nav>`; use `<a>` for navigation, `<button>` for actions (e.g. language switch).
- **Lists**: `<ul>`/`<ol>` for link or item lists; do not use divs for lists.
- **Images**: Always descriptive `alt` (e.g. "Naldson Bento Chagas, backend developer").
- **Accessibility**: Correct `lang` on `<html>` (e.g. `lang="en"` or `lang="pt"`); landmarks and labels when needed.

## SEO

- **Title**: Unique and descriptive per route (e.g. "Naldson Bento Chagas | Senior Backend Developer").
- **Meta**: Unique `description` per page; basic Open Graph when relevant (title, description, image).
- **URLs**: Friendly and stable; language support via URL or `hreflang`/`lang` per i18n setup.
- **Content**: Important text in HTML (not only in images); headings that reflect the content.
- **Performance**: Fast load and critical content in first paint (see performance rules).

## Landmarks example

```html
<header>...</header>
<nav aria-label="Main">...</nav>
<main>
  <section id="about" aria-labelledby="about-heading">...</section>
  <section id="cases">...</section>
</main>
<footer id="contact">...</footer>
```
